I don't see how they are going to get any significant money from her.
She seems pretty much broke to me. I also suspect that her legal defense
costs will be paid by the taxpayers if this is a criminal case. Whoever
is running the RIAA's campaign hasn't a clue about public opinion and
how to manage a campaign.

I hardly buy any music anymore -- I still will buy Tom Petty and the
Heartbreakers stuff (gosh I love that band), but thats about it any
more. I don't download songs illegally either, and never have. I am just
tired of the same crap the music industry serves up.

The RIAA's argument that the downturn in music sales is completely due
to illegal downloading is disingenuous at best, and an outright lie at
worst.

Stealing music is a crime, no argument from me, but it would be smarter
to promote and produce better music because in the long run the music
business will reap far more money that way as opposed to taking
'recreational' low scale downloaders to court. As far as locking all the
content down with DRM goes, the cost associated with that path is huge
as well, and the army of hackers has proven to be far better at picking
the locks than the rights-holders ever imagined. I am actually very
sympathetic to the hackers who use the new 'tools' to unlock content so
they can exercise their fair use rights.

Interesting to see organizations like the RIAA and companies like
DirecTV taking their customers to court. Wonder if it will buy them any
'friends?'

