Bobby The D &lt;bobbyt ... @bigfoot.com&gt; wrote:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;This brings up a bigger issue. We now have an entire generation that
&gt;seems to feel that music is &quot;supposed&quot; to be free. Draconian laws are
&gt;not gonna work any more than prohibition worked in the 1920s. Any
&gt;ideas on how this problem can be solved?

"/> Yes. A new business model. Record companies sell songs cheap (around
$.50, or maybe a monthly &quot;all you can eat&quot; subscription. Songs come
with a _brief_ ad. Part of the revenue comes from advertising, some
from subscriptions/direct sales. Also, downloaded songs are
watermarked, so illegal copies can be traced back to whoever put them
on the net, although there may not be a whole lot to be done without
pissing off your whole customer base.

Let's face it. It costs 10 cents to produce a CD or DVD. The sales
price is nearly $20. Say 40% goes to the store, and probably at
least 25% to the distributor. That leaves $7 for the record company,
to pay for:
. one-time costs: studio, mixing, etc.
. advertising
. the 10 cents for the CD
. 5 cents more for the jewelbox and &quot;covers&quot;
. royalties to the composer and/or lyricist
. royalties to the performers.
. profit! necessary, else the whole business goes away.
. &quot;risk&quot; costs: sometimes the record company doesn't get back the
money it spent on the above four items.

A 1:15:00 CD will hold between 10 and 20 songs, depending on length.
So that's somewhere between 35 and 70 cents per song. If they sell
music over the internet, they don't have to pay distributors or record
stores. (Oh, add a couple of cents to the above costs for
bandwidth...)

Suddenly the cost model doesn't look so bad. I'm guessing the profit
_per copy_ will go down, and maybe the royalties will be a little less
rich (which is bad for beginning songwriters &amp; performers). But at
that price, I bet even teenagers won't be so willing to risk getting
caught and having to pay damages.

And best of all, I'll also bet that:
1. Their sales would go way up, because people would be a lot more
willing to spend $.50 to see if they like a song than $18-20 on
a CD that might have 1 or 2 songs they really like.
2. They get feedback faster. That means they can direct their
efforts more toward those songs, groups, etc. that produce
sales _this month_.

The history of technology shows that people (and corporations) that
_adapt_ to the new technology end up making _more_ money than they did
before the change. All the way back to &quot;radio is going to ruin our
record sales&quot;. Then it was wire recorders. Then tape recorders.
Than portable CD recorders. Then VCRs. Tivos. Every time, those who
got on the horse and hung on for dear life made money hand over fist.
The only losers were the ones who insisted the horse had to be tied
up inside a corral.
