"/> Clearly the case, since the statutory damages provision is part of the
1976 revisions to the copyright laws, and before that the 1909 act.

The response of Congress to a copyright infringer not having assets
comparable to the damage done has been to strength the criminal
provisions of the copyright laws, including an alternative to the
past requirement that criminal infringement had to be done not only
willfully, but &quot;for purposes of commercial advantage or private
financial gain.&quot; (The NET Act, passed in 1997.)

There is legislation pending (H.R. 4077, for example) that would remove
the &quot;willful&quot; requirement for large public distributions.

Maybe they will get to wear those Nikes in federal prison ...

Note that criminal penalties for copyright infringement are not a
new thing, but have been part of United States copyright law for
over a hundred years. And even before that, one could be jailed
if one could not pay a debt or a judgement.

